[1] Cholera - Nigeria
Date: Thu 3 Mar 2022
Source: Punch Nigeria [edited]
https://punchng.com/470-fresh-cholera-cases-recorded-in-january/


The Nigeria Centre for Disease Control (NCDC) has announced that 470 fresh suspected cases of cholera and 9 deaths have been reported in the first 4 weeks of this year [2022]. The centre also said children from the age of 5 and below were the most affected. According to the NCDC, a total of 10 states have reported suspected cholera cases in 2022. The states are Abia, Adamawa, Bauchi, Bayelsa, Borno, Cross River, Kwara, Lagos, Taraba and Zamfara.

The centre, in its latest cholera report, stated, "Of all the suspected cases, 45% are males and 55% are females. Three states, namely, Taraba (201), Borno (88) and Adamawa (56), account for 73% of all cumulative cases. Ten local government areas across the 5 states of Borno, Adamawa, Taraba, Bayelsa and Kwara reported more than 10 cases each in 2022."

The centre stated, "Some of the challenges are difficulty in accessing some communities due to security concerns, open defecation in affected communities, and lack of potable drinking water in some rural areas and urban slums. The challenges also include inadequate health facility infrastructure and cholera commodities for management of patients, inadequate trained personnel in states for case management, and poor and inconsistent reporting from states."

The NCDC added that it would continue training in cholera surveillance, hotspot mapping and developing state-level preparedness and response plans, as well as maintaining communication with and support to states.

[Byline: Deborah Tolu-Kolawole]

