[3] Diarrhea - South Africa (Cape Town)
Date: Thu 3 Mar 2022
Source: Independent Online (IOL) [abridged, edited]
https://bit.ly/3pFxGWh


The City of Cape Town yesterday [2 Mar 2022] announced its clinics had reported a major spike in diarrhea cases amid the surge season. Diarrhea is a fairly common ailment during the warmer months, and it remains one of the biggest threats to children under 5. It is one of the leading causes of death in this age-group in developing countries. Between November and May, the number of diarrhea cases typically increases throughout the population as the warmer weather promotes the spread of germs. This is also known as surge season.

Mayoral committee member for community services and health, Councillor Patricia Van der Ross, said there had been a 70% increase in children younger than 5 presenting with diarrhea at clinics compared to the same time in 2021. "Surge season data tracks cases of diarrhea, pneumonia and severe acute malnutrition in young children. If these are not diagnosed timely and treated, it can have life-threatening consequences.

"The very hot conditions in the city have led to a noticeable increase in the number of children brought to health facilities with symptoms like diarrhea, vomiting and dehydration," Van der Ross said. During January 2021, city clinics dealt with 1710 cases. This increased to 2908 cases during January 2022.

Van der Ross said the clinics provided services to diagnose and treat diarrhea, pneumonia, malnutrition and a number of other ailments that affect children.

[Byline: Robin-Lee Francke]

